Sure! Here's a JavaScript function that reverses a string without using the built-in reverse() method:

```javascript
function reverseString(str) {
  let reversed = '';
  for (let i = str.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    reversed += str[i];
  }
  return reversed;
}
```

You can use this function by passing a string as an argument, like this:

```javascript
let originalString = "Hello, World!";
let reversedString = reverseString(originalString);
console.log(reversedString); // Output: "!dlroW ,olleH"
```

This function works by iterating through the characters of the input string in reverse order and building a new string with those characters.
